On the supposition that the words diverso ex hoste and utroque ab litore refer to victories in the East and VVest, it has been thought that the western victory is that gained over the Cantabri in Spain, Β. This difficulty is however avoided if we adopt Prof. Nettleship's suggestion that Virgil is alluding to the Morini and the Dalmatians. The former had been subdued by Julius Caesar and again by C. Carrinas, the latter by Vatinius in 45 B.C. and by Augustus in 34 B.C.
